  "prompt": "What are Audio Codecs?",
  "response": "Audio codecs are software or hardware devices that encode and decode digital audio data. The term \"codec\" stands for \"coder-decoder.\" These devices use audio compression algorithms to reduce the data size of digital audio while maintaining its quality. This makes it possible to store or transmit audio more efficiently.\n\nThere are several different types of audio codecs, each using different compression techniques and offering different levels of quality and file size. Some popular audio codecs include MP3, AAC, and WMA. MP3 is one of the most widely used audio codecs, and it uses a lossy compression algorithm, which means that some of the audio data is discarded during the encoding process. AAC and WMA are also lossy codecs, but they use more advanced compression techniques and can provide higher quality audio at lower bitrates.\n\nIn addition to lossy codecs, there are also lossless audio codecs, such as FLAC and ALAC. These codecs use compression algorithms that preserve all of the original audio data, resulting in larger file sizes but higher audio quality.\n\nAudio codecs are used in a wide range of applications, including music streaming, video conferencing, and voice over IP (VoIP) communications. They are essential for enabling efficient transmission and storage of digital audio.",
